Pandas: Cuddliest of all Bears
What do you know about giant pandas?
Read and complete the article to ﬁnd out more about these cuddly black and white bears.

Introduction
The giant panda has a distinctive ______ head
with _______ eye patches, ears and shoulders.
Unlike other bear species, giant pandas are
__________ , spending up to 12 hours a day
chewing bamboo shoots and roots. Because
of poaching and habitat loss, they are
extremely
_________ , occurring in small populations in
the bamboo forests of China. Despite being
the subject of major international
conservation efforts, wild populations of
giant pandas
_____ not be enough to save this species.
The giant panda has a distinctive white head
with black eye patches, ears and shoulders.
Unlike other bear species, giant pandas are
herbivorous, spending up to 12 hours a day
chewing bamboo shoots and roots. Because
of poaching and habitat loss, they are
extremely rare, occurring in small
populations in the bamboo forests of China.
Despite being the subject of major
international conservation efforts, wild
populations of giant pandas
can not be enough to save this species.
Panda’s Territory: Where do pandas
come from?
Giant pandas ________ in the bamboo forests
of China for millions years and have been
honored by the Chinese for a very long time.
In fact, giant pandas _______ in Chinese art for
thousands of years. Because the giant panda
is considered a national treasure in China, it is
protected by law so that it ___________ extinct.
Giant pandas have lived in the bamboo
forests of China for millions years and have
been honored by the Chinese for a very long
time. In fact, giant pandas have appeared in
Chinese art for thousands of years. Because
the giant panda is considered a national
treasure in China, it is protected by law so
that it does not become extinct.
Although giant pandas have long been
known to the Chinese, they are a recent
discovery for people living outside of China.
The ﬁrst westerner to observe a live giant
panda in the wild was a German zoologist
named Hugo Weigold. In 1916, he had
bought a cub while he was on expedition.
2
Although giant pandas have long been
known to the Chinese, they ______ a recent
discovery for people living outside of China.
The ﬁrst westerner to observe a live giant
panda in the wild ______ a German zoologist
named Hugo Weigold. In 1916, he ________ a
cub while he was on expedition.
At Panda’s Place: Where do pandas
live?
There is only one place where giant pandas
________ in the wild: high in the mountains of
central China. There, they ________ in cold and
rainy bamboo forests that are often misty
and shrouded in heavy clouds. Once upon a
time, giant pandas _______ in lowland areas.
However, as people _________ more and more
farms and cities on that land, the giant
pandas were forced up into the mountains.
Today, they _________ at elevations of 5,000 to
10,000 feet.
There is only one place where giant pandas
live in the wild: high in the mountains of
central China. There, they live in cold and
rainy bamboo forests that are often misty
and shrouded in heavy clouds. Once upon a
time, giant pandas lived in lowland areas.
However, as people had built more and
more farms and cities on that land, the giant
pandas were forced up into the mountains.
Today, they live at elevations of 5,000 to
10,000 feet.
